      ],
      "correctOption": 3,
      "solution": "<img src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/0eWJ1GR4NlPlHtCAA/JcKpG9j1HxOTKnxTDPRT5phkqwjw5/4htZqKPCHa5BflRbaAGghq/image.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;  height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"JEE Main 2019 (Online) 12th January Evening Slot Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 152 English Explanation 1\">\n<br>As here HBr is present in excess, so HBr will react to alkene and  ether part sinultaneously. \n<br><br>According to Markovnikov rule. Carbocation close to benzene ring is more stable. \n<br><br>In the given reagent, carbocation is $$ \\to $$\n<br><br><img src=\"https://imagex.cdn.examgoal.net/uMEPgtUUGX18RMchK/GNTt0kIoEkHFsiscqq58S410cQRF1/3Ggm25ISZHjWNbVWkopfsy/image.png\" style=\"max-width: 100%;  height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"JEE Main 2019 (Online) 12th January Evening Slot Chemistry - Haloalkanes and Haloarenes Question 152 English Explanation 2\">\n<br>So in HBr, Br<sup>$$-$$</sup> adds to the carbocation.\n<br><br>And in the ether part because of lone pair of oxygen, it will take part in resonance a double bond will create between O atom and benzene ring. So, this bond will be stronger. That is why CH<sub>3</sub> $$-$$ O bond will break.",
